(129, 1, '2012-10-01 15:46:49', '2012-10-01 15:46:49', '<ul>\n	<li>\n<h1 class="inline moreleading">Taking The GED<sup>®</sup> Test is an important step.</h1>\n<h2 class="inline moreleading">Use the links below to find programs to prepare, testing locations, and much more.</h2>\n&nbsp;\nIf your next step involves graduating from high school or taking the GED<sup>&reg;</sup> test (high school equivalency degree test), you’re in luck. There are 84 testing sites across the state, offered through Adult and Community Education programs. These programs offer orientation classes and pre-testing as well.\n\nView Information about <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/hsc.htm" target="_blank">GED<sup>&reg;</sup> &amp; high school diploma programs</a> through Maine Adult Education, along with the list of <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/data/GED2010.pdf" target="_blank">locations that offer GED<sup>&reg;</sup> testing programs</a> in Maine. Another valuable resource to prospective test takers can be found at the <a title="GED Test Services website" href="http://www.gedtestingservice.com/testers/test-taker-home" target="_blank">GED<sup>&reg;</sup> Testing Service website</a>.</li>\n	<li>\n<h3>LINKS &amp; RESOURCES</h3>\n[accordion title="Take a practice test"]<a href="http://www.maine.gov/msl/commons/learnexp/index.shtml" target="_blank">The Maine State Library</a> offers a variety of study aids and practice tests. Also refer to the <a href="http://www.maineadulted.org/" target="_blank">Maine Adult Education website</a> to see what’s available in your area.[/accordion][accordion title="Is Your Next Step College?"]Adult Education can help you explore college options as well. <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/transitions.htm" target="_blank">The College Transitions Program</a> (offered through Adult Education programs around the state) helps adult students transition into college. Get support with applications and financial aid, college prep classes, college and career planning, placement testing, and individual advising.\n\nAdults in Maine who want to go to community college, as well as some of the other public Universities, may need to take the placement test Accuplacer. The ACCUPLACER® is a set of exams that quickly and accurately assess reading, writing, math, and computer skills. This process is designed to evaluate readiness for college level work. Individual colleges and universities administer the tests, so just ask if it’s a requirement that applies to you and if so, when, where and how you can take the test. If you’re nervous about these placement tests, talk with your local adult education office or College Transitions counselor. Maine''s Career and Technical Education centers, community colleges and state universities use the ACCUPLACER® extensively to track achievement and to determine course placements.  For more information go to:  <a title="Maine DOE Accuplacer" href="http://www.maine.gov/education/mhsa/accuplacer.html" target="_blank">Maine DOE Accuplacer Page</a>.[/accordion][accordion title="Get College Credit for Work Experience"]\n\nPrior Learning Assessment or PLA is a way that you can receive college credit for what you’ve learned through work. This can save you time and money if you’re planning to get a college degree by eliminating the number of classes you may need to take. Colleges and universities in Maine have different methods of awarding credit based on each school''s academic requirements.\n\nTo see information about PLA at the University of Maine at Augusta: <a href="http://www.uma.edu/testingassessment.html" target="_blank">Click here</a>.\n\nTo see information about PLA at the University of Southern Maine: <a href="http://www.usm.maine.edu/pla" target="_blank">Click here</a>.\n\nTo see information about PLA at Saint Joseph’s College of Maine: <a href="http://online.sjcme.edu/continuing-education-units-opportunities.php" target="_blank">Click here</a>.\n\n<a href="http://www.cael.org/home" target="_blank">The Center for Adult &amp; Experiential Learning (CAEL)</a> is a great resource to learn about PLA.\n\n[/accordion][accordion title="Jobs in Maine"]See the list of <a title="High-Growth Jobs in Maine" href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/jobs/">jobs that are growing in Maine</a> that require a high school diploma or high school equivalency degree.[/accordion]</li>\n</ul>', 'GED<sup>&reg;</sup> testing', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '18-autosave', '', '', '2012-10-01 15:46:49', '2012-10-01 15:46:49', '', 18, 'http://www.nextstepmaine.org/18-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2073, 2, '2012-06-29 16:41:00', '2012-06-29 16:41:00', '<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<h1><span>1)</span>Get a GED</h1>\r\nIf your next step involves graduating from high school or taking the GED test (Test for General Educational Development), you’re in luck. There are 84 testing sites across the state, offered through Adult and Community Education programs. These programs offer orientation classes and pre-testing as well.\r\n\r\nView Information about <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/hsc.htm" target="_blank">GED &amp; high school diploma programs</a> through Maine Adult Education, along with the list of <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/data/testcenters.pdf" target="_blank">locations that offer GED testing programs</a> in Maine.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<h1><span>2)</span>LINKS &amp; RESOURCES</h1>\r\n[accordion title="Take a practice test"]<a href="http://www.maine.gov/msl/commons/learnexp/index.shtml" target="_blank">The Maine State Library</a> offers a variety of study aids and practice tests, including GED. Also refer to the <a href="http://www.maineadulted.org/" target="_blank">Maine Adult Education website</a> to see what’s available in your area.[/accordion][accordion title="Is Your Next Step College?"]Adult Education can help you explore college options as well. <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/transitions/mctp%20description%20revised%202010.doc" target="_blank">The College Transitions Program</a>(offered through Adult Education programs around the state)helps adult students transition into college. Get support with applications and financial aid, college prep classes, college and career planning, placement testing, and individual advising. See the list of the <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/transitions/MCT.Contact._info.pdf" target="_blank">Colleges Transitions program locations</a>.[/accordion][accordion title="Get College Credit for Work Experience"]Prior Learning Assessment or PLA is a way that you can receive college credit for what you’ve learned through work. This can save you time and money if you’re planning to get a college degree by eliminating the number of classes you may need to take. Colleges and universities in Maine have different methods of awarding credit based on each school''s academic requirements.\r\nView information about PLA at the <a href="http://www.uma.edu/testingassessment.html" target="_blank">University of Maine at Augusta</a> or information about PLA at the <a href="http://www.usm.maine.edu/pla" target="_blank">University of Southern Maine</a>.\r\nThe <a href="http://www.cael.org/home" target="_blank">Center for Adult &amp; Experiential Learning (CAEL)</a> is also a great resource to learn about PLA[/accordion][accordion title="Jobs in Maine"]See the list of <a href="http://www.maine.gov/labor/labor_stats/jobs_in_demand.shtml" target="_blank">jobs that are growing in Maine</a> that require a high school diploma or GED.[/accordion]</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Get a GED', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '18-revision-14', '', '', '2012-06-29 16:41:00', '2012-06-29 16:41:00', '', 18, 'http://www.nextstepmaine.org/18-revision-14/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(130, 2, '2012-06-12 19:53:19', '2012-06-12 19:53:19', '<strong>Get a GED</strong>\r\n\r\nIf your next step involves graduating from high school or taking the GED test (Test for General Educational Development), you’re in luck.  There are 84 testing sites across the state, offered through Adult and Community Education programs.  These programs offer orientation classes and pre-testing as well.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nClick here for information about GED &amp; high school diploma programs through Maine Adult Education: <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/hsc.htm">http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/hsc.htm</a>\r\n\r\nClick here for the list of locations that offer GED testing programs in Maine:  <a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/data/testcenters.pdf">http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/data/testcenters.pdf</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>LINKS &amp; RESOURCES</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Take a practice test:  </strong>The Maine State Library offers a variety of study aids and practice tests, including GED,  <strong>http://www.maine.gov/msl/commons/learnexp/index.shtml</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Adult Education Courses:</strong>  See what’s available in your area here:<strong>  </strong><a href="http://www.maineadulted.org/"><strong>http://www.maineadulted.org/</strong></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Is Your Next Step College?</strong>\r\n\r\nAdult Education can help you explore college options as well. The College Transitions Program<strong> </strong>(offered through Adult Education programs around the state)<strong> </strong>helps adult students transition into college. Get support with applications and financial aid, college prep classes, college and career planning, placement testing, and individual advising.\r\n\r\n<strong>For a more complete description of the program:  </strong><a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/transitions/mctp%20description%20revised%202010.doc"><strong>MCTP Description</strong></a><strong>(rtf) </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>For the location of a Colleges Transitions program:  </strong><a href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/transitions/MCT.Contact._info.pdf"><strong>College Transitions Programs</strong></a><strong> (PDF) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Get College Credit for Work Experience:</strong> Prior Learning Assessment or PLA is a way that you can receive college credit for what you’ve learned through work.  This can save you time and money if you’re planning to get a college degree by eliminating the number of classes you may need to take.  Colleges and universities in Maine have different methods of awarding credit based on each school''s academic requirements.\r\n\r\nTo see information about PLA at the University of Maine at Augusta:<strong> </strong><a href="http://www.uma.edu/testingassessment.html"><strong>www.uma.edu/testingassessment.html</strong></a>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>To see information about PLA at the University of Southern Maine:<strong>  </strong><a href="http://www.usm.maine.edu/pla"><strong>www.usm.maine.edu/pla</strong></a>\r\n\r\nThe Center for Adult &amp; Experiential Learning (CAEL) is a great resource to learn about PLA:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.cael.org/home"><strong>http://www.cael.org/home</strong><strong></strong></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jobs in Maine</strong><strong>: </strong><a href="http://www.maine.gov/labor/labor_stats/jobs_in_demand.shtml"><strong>See jobs that are growing in Maine that require a high school diploma or GED.</strong></a>', 'Get a GED', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '18-revision-4', '', '', '2012-06-12 19:53:19', '2012-06-12 19:53:19', '', 18, 'http://www.nextstepmaine.org/18-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
