ve learned through work. This can save you time and money if you’re planning to get a college degree by eliminating the number of classes you may need to take. Colleges and universities in Maine have different methods of awarding credit based on each school''s academic requirements.\r\nView information about PLA at the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.uma.edu/testingassessment.html">University of Maine at Augusta</a> or information about PLA at the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.usm.maine.edu/pla">University of Southern Maine</a>.\r\nThe <a target="_blank" href="http://www.cael.org/home">Center for Adult &amp; Experiential Learning (CAEL)</a> is also a great resource to learn about PLA[/accordion][accordion title="Jobs in Maine"]See the list of <a target="_blank" href="http://www.maine.gov/labor/labor_stats/jobs_in_demand.shtml">jobs that are growing in Maine</a> that require a high school diploma or GED.[/accordion]</li></ul>', 'Get a GED', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '18-revision-10', '', '', '2012-06-12 20:10:32', '2012-06-12 20:10:32', '', 18, 'http://www.nextstepmaine.org/18-revision-10/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(140, 2, '2012-06-12 20:30:06', '2012-06-12 20:30:06', '<ul><li><h1><span>1)</span>Change My Career</h1>\r\nThe majority of us have multiple careers during our lifetimes.  If you’re considering making a change, we’ve compiled some resources to help.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.mainecareercenter.com/employment/training-adults/index.shtml" target="_blank">Maine’s Career Centers</a> are a great place to start assessing what your next step might be. They can provide information about how to decide what career is right for you, and how to get the right training to be qualified. To see the full list of career center locations <a href="http://www.mainecareercenter.com/locations/index.shtml" target="_blank">Click here</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.maine.gov/labor/labor_stats/jobs_in_demand.shtml" target="_blank">Jobs in demand in Maine</a> provides a list of job fields around Maine that are desired by employers.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.mainecareercenter.com/employment/search/index.shtml" target="_blank">The Maine Job Bank</a> also has a list of jobs around the state of Maine that are desired by employers.\r\n\r\n<h2>DEGREES &amp; CERTIFICATES</h2>Browse 2 or 4 year degree programs, certificates or advanced degrees available in Maine.\r\n<ul><li><a href="">Associates Degrees (2 Year)</a></li><li><a href="">Bachelors Degrees (4 Year)</a></li><li><a href="">Certificates</a></li><li><a href="">Advanced Degrees</a></li></ul></li><li><h1><span>1)</span>Links and Resources</h1>[accordion title="Examination Preparation"]<a href="http://www.maine.gov/msl/commons/learnexp/index.shtml" target="_blank">LearningExpress Library</a> is offered by the Maine State Library and features over 770 practice tests, tutorials, and eBooks related to job search and workplace skills improvement, career certification and licensing exam preparation, college entrance and graduate school admissions exam preparation, GED exam preparation, and basic skills improvement in reading, writing, and math, for all ages.\r\n\r\nYou will get immediate scoring, complete answer explanations, and an individualized analysis of your results.  In addition, you will find interactive popular software tutorials/courses that are video-based and allow you to learn at your own pace.[/accordion]</li></ul>', 'Change My Career', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '27-revision-15', '', '', '2012-06-12 20:30:06', '2012-06-12 20:30:06', '', 27, 'http://www.nextstepmaine.org/27-revision-15/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2082, 2, '2012-06-26 18:48:55', '2012-06-26 18:48:55', '<ul><li><h1><span>1)</span>Finish College</h1>\r\nIf you started college and didn’t complete a degree, you are not alone. There are over 218,000 people in Maine who are in exactly the same position. Finishing your degree could help you make a career change, increase your income, inspire your kids to finish college themselves, or just give you the satisfaction of knowing you did it. Use this site to get the resources and information you need to get back into the game.\r\n\r\nMore and more jobs in the future will require a college degree of some kind.  Workers who have college degrees also earn more over their lifetimes than those who don’t. So, think about finishing your degree.\r\n\r\n<h2>DEGREES &amp; CERTIFICATES</h2>Browse 2 or 4 year degree programs, certificates or advanced degrees available in Maine.\r\n<ul><li><a href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/programs/associate" title="Associate Degrees in Maine">Associates Degrees (2 Year)</a></li><li><a href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/programs/bachelor" title="Bachelor Degrees in Maine">Bachelors Degrees (4 Year)</a></li><li><a href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/programs/certificate" title="Certificates in Maine">Certificates</a></li><li><a href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/programs/master" title="Masters Degrees in Maine">Advanced Degrees</a></li></ul></li><li><h1><span>2)</span>LINKS &amp; RESOURCES</h1>[accordion title="Get Help from Your Employer"]If you have a job, your first step should be to find out what supports your employer may offer to further your education and training.  Many employers offer tuition assistance, flexible scheduling or on-site training to help increase employees’ skills &amp; knowledge. If your employer is part of the Maine Employers’ Initiative, you are entitled to tuition discounts from several institutions in Maine: If your employer is on <a href="http://www.mdf.org/mei_employers.php" target="_blank">this list</a>, ask them about it![/accordion][accordion title="Transfer Your Credits"]The University of Maine System will accept credits within the system as long as a C- or higher grade was achieved in the course, and will consider courses from other accredited institutions. Go to the transfer equivalency system to find more details about your particular credits: <a href="https://peportal.maine.edu/psp/PAPRD89/EMPLOYEE/CSPRDST/c/UM_SA.UM_TRNSFER_GUEST.GBL?PORTALPARAM_PTCNAV=UM_TRNFR_COURSE_CREDIT&amp;EOPP.SCNode=EMPL&amp;EOPP.SCPortal=EMPLOYEE&amp;EOPP.SCName=ADMN_UM_CLASS_SRCH_QCKLINLS&amp;EOPP.SCLabel=UM_CLASS_SRCH_QCKLINLS&amp;EOPP.SCPTcname=&amp;FolderPath=PORTAL_ROOT_OBJECT.PORTAL_BASE_DATA.CO_NAVIGATION_COLLECTIONS.ADMN_UM_CLASS_SRCH_QCKLINLS.ADMN_S200907291138273689687795&amp;IsFolder=false" target="_blank">UMaine System Transfer Equivalency System</a>\r\n\r\nTo find out how to transfer your credits to other institutions in Maine, you will need to contact each institution directly. Many of the community colleges have transfer agreements with other colleges and universities in Maine. You can contact the community college you attended to find out where the credits will easily transfer as well.[/accordion][accordion title="Get College Credit for Work Experience"]Prior Learning Assessment or PLA is a way that you can receive college credit for what you’ve learned through work. This can save you time and money if you’re planning to get a college degree by eliminating the number of classes you may need to take. Colleges and universities in Maine have different methods of awarding credit based on each school''s academic requirements.\r\n\r\nTo see information about PLA at the University of Maine at Augusta: <a href="http://www.uma.edu/testingassessment.html" target="_blank">Click here</a>.\r\n\r\nTo see information about PLA at the University of Southern Maine: <a href="http://www.usm.maine.edu/pla" target="_blank">Click here</a>.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.cael.org/home" target="_blank">The Center for Adult &amp; Experiential Learning (CAEL)</a> is a great resource to learn about PLA.[/accordion][accordion title="Degrees &amp; Certifications"]Browse 2 or 4 year degree programs, certificates or advanced degrees available in Maine.\r\nAssociates Degrees (2 Year)\r\nBachelors Degrees (4 Year)\r\nCertificates\r\nAdvanced Degrees[/accordion][accordion title="Maine Jobs in Demand"]<a href="http://www.maine.gov/labor/labor_stats/jobs_in_demand.shtml#bachelors" target="_blank">Jobs you could do in Maine with a bachelor’s degree</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.maine.gov/labor/labor_stats/jobs_in_demand.shtml#associate" target="_blank">Jobs you can do in Maine with an associate’s degree</a>[/accordion]</li><li><h1><span>3)</span>Pay for College:</h1>[accordion title="Finance Authority of Maine"]The Finance Authority of Maine provides free information on planning and paying for college, career preparation and financial education, including responsible borrowing. <a href="http://www.famemaine.com/Education_Home.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.famemaine.com/Education_Home.aspx</a>\r\n\r\nFAME has tools and information specifically to help adult students plan for and start college. Find everything here from choosing a career or college, to balancing school with work and family, to applying to college and paying for school, and much more: <a href="http://www.famemaine.com/files/Pages/education/students_and_families/Non-Traditional_Students.aspx" target="_blank">Click here to access the FAME tools.</a>[/accordion]</li><li><h1><span>4)</span>FAQ</h1>[accordion title="Should I take an online program?"]Many of the programs that work best for adult students who have jobs, families and other obligations are online programs. This option may or may not work for you. Some of the Adult Education programs offer introductory courses in online learning: <a href="http://www.maineadulted.org/" target="_blank">Maine Adult Education</a>\r\n\r\nThere are other assessments and guides you can take a look at to assess whether you’re a good candidate for online classes &amp; programs:\r\n\r\nFor example, here is the Saint Joseph’s College of Maine online guide:  <a href="http://online.sjcme.edu/pdf/learningonlineguide.pdf" target="_blank">http://online.sjcme.edu/pdf/learningonlineguide.pdf</a>[/accordion]</li></ul>', 'Finish College', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '25-revision-55', '', '', '2012-06-26 18:48:55', '2012-06-26 18:48:55', '', 25, 'http://www.nextstepmaine.org/25-revision-55/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2081, 2, '2012-06-26 18:46:34', '2012-06-26 18:46:34', '<ul><li><h1><span>1)</span>Start College</h1>\r\nThere are lots of reasons that your next step should be to start college: to encourage your kids to go to college, change careers or earn a bigger paycheck, or simply to feel the sense of accomplishment that comes with that diploma.\r\n\r\nMore and more jobs in the future will require a college degree of some kind. Workers who have college degrees also earn more over their lifetimes than those who don’t. So, college may be a smart next step for you.\r\n\r\nThe question is: where do you start? Good news: there are a lot of resources available to you in Maine. On this site, you can explore jobs that require a college degree and are growing in Maine. You can browse or search for programs and institutions that might be of interest to you. You can find help figuring out how to pay for college, and much more.\r\n\r\n<h2>DEGREES &amp; CERTIFICATES</h2>Browse 2 or 4 year degree programs, certificates or advanced degrees available in Maine.\r\n<ul><li><a href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/programs/associate" title="Associate Degrees in Maine">Associates Degrees (2 Year)</a></li><li><a href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/programs/bachelor" title="Bachelor Degrees in Maine">Bachelors Degrees (4 Year)</a></li><li><a href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/programs/certificate" title="Certificates in Maine">Certificates</a></li><li><a href="http://www.nextstepmaine.org/programs/master" title="Masters Degrees in Maine">Advanced Degrees</a></li></ul></li><li><h1><span>2)</span>LINKS &amp; RESOURCES</h1>[accordion title="Get Help from Your Employer"]If you have a job, your first step should be to find out what supports your employer may offer to further your education and training.  Many employers offer tuition assistance, flexible scheduling or on-site training to help increase employees’ skills &amp; knowledge. If your employer is part of the Maine Employers’ Initiative, you are entitled to tuition discounts from several institutions in Maine: If your employer is on <a target="_blank" href="http://www.mdf.org/mei_employers.php">this list</a>, ask them about it![/accordion][accordion title="The College Transitions Program"]The College Transitions Program is a great first step. Adult Education can help you explore your college options, figure out if you’re ready – and if you’re not ready, they’ll help you get ready. The Maine College Transitions Program (offered through Adult Education programs around the state)<strong> </strong>is designed to help adult students transition into college. They will provide support with applications and financial aid, college prep classes, college and career planning, placement testing, and individual advising. For a more complete description of the program: <a target="_blank" href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/transitions/mctp%20description%20revised%202010.doc">Click here</a>. For the location of a College''s Transitions program: <a target="_blank" href="http://www.maine.gov/education/aded/dev/transitions/MCT.Contact._info.pdf">Click here</a>.[/accordion][accordion title="College Entrance Examination Preparation"]<a target="_blank" href="http://www.maine.gov/msl/commons/learnexp/index.shtml" target="_blank">LearningExpress Library</a> is offered by the Maine State Library and features over 770 practice tests, tutorials, and eBooks related to job search and workplace skills improvement, career certification and licensing exam preparation, college entrance and graduate school admissions exam preparation, GED exam preparation, and basic skills improvement in reading, writing, and math, for all ages.\r\n\r\nYou will get immediate scoring, complete answer explanations, and an individualized analysis of your results. In addition, you will find interactive popular software tutorials/courses that are video-based and allow you to learn at your own pace.[/accordion][accordion title="Get College Credit for Work Experience"]Prior Learning Assessment or PLA is a way that you can receive college credit for what you’ve learned through work. This can save you time and money if you’re planning to get a college degree by eliminating the number of classes you may need to take. Colleges and universities in Maine have different methods of awarding credit based on each school''s academic requirements.\r\n\r\nTo see information about PLA at the University of Maine at Augusta: <a target="_blank" href="http://www.uma.edu/testingassessment.html">Click here</a>.\r\n\r\nTo see information about PLA at the University of Southern Maine: <a target="_blank" href="http://www.usm.maine.edu/pla">CLick here</a>.\r\n\r\n<a target="_blank" href="http://www.cael.org/home">The Center for Adult &amp; Experiential Learning (CAEL)</a> is a great resource to learn about PLA.[/accordion][accordion title="Jobs in Maine"]<a target="_blank" href="http://www.maine.gov/labor/labor_stats/jobs_in_demand.shtml#associates">Jobs you can do in Maine with an associate’s degree</a>.\r\n<a target="_blank" href="http://www.maine.gov/labor/labor_stats/jobs_in_demand.shtml#bachelors">Jobs you could do in Maine with a bachelor’s degree</a>.[/accordion]</li><li><h1><span>3)</span>Pay for College</h2>[accordion title="Finance Authority of Maine"]<a target="_blank" href="http://www.famemaine.com/Education_Home.aspx">The Finance Authority of Maine</a> provides free information on planning and paying for college, career preparation and financial education, including responsible borrowing. \r\n\r\nFAME has tools and information specifically to help adult students plan for and start college. Find everything here from choosing a career or college, to balancing school with work and family, to applying to college and paying for school, and much more: To access the FAME tools, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.famemaine.com/files/Pages/education/students_and_families/Non-Traditional_Students.aspx">CLick here</a>.[/accordion]</li><li><h1><span>4)</span>FAQ</h1>[accordion title="Should I take an online program?"]Many of the programs that work best for adult students who have jobs, families and other obligations are online programs. This option may or may not work for you. Some of the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.maineadulted.org/">Maine Adult Education</a> programs offer introductory courses in online learning.\r\n\r\nThere are other assessments and guides you can take a look at to assess whether you’re a good candidate for online classes &amp; programs. For example, the <a target="_blank" href="http://online.sjcme.edu/pdf/learningonlineguide.pdf">Saint Joseph’s College of Maine online guide</a>[/accordion]</li></ul>', 'Start College', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '20-revision-16', '', '', '2012-06-26 18:46:34', '2012-06-26 18:46:34', '', 20, 'http://www.nextstepmaine.org/20-revision-16/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
